{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3425607,"name":"Sam","username":"Paraduks","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/ea5d25/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-09-20T20:55:04.127Z","cooked":"<p>Hello all,<br>
I am thinking through improvements to our team’s autonomous system, and I am unsure what tools / methods satisfy the requirements I am looking for.  Here’s the workflow that I would like:</p>
<ol>
<li>I find our alliance partners to talk strategy for a match.  I bring a tablet / laptop to the meeting.  On that device, I have a PathPlanner-like gui where I can keyframe our robot’s autonomous path and play it back.  I have preset auto paths, but I can edit and customize any part of the path in the moment as we discuss strategy.</li>
<li>We decide on auto routines.  I come back to the pit and load the auto onto the driver station laptop (which stays at the pit for use in testing).  Loading the auto is done through a thumb drive, USB cord, qr code, or whatever works best.</li>
<li>As we prepare for the match, I can continue to edit the auto however I want, through the same gui, on the driver station laptop.  I can also edit setpoints, motor speeds, etc.  When I am done, I <em>lock</em> the auto, signifying that it is completed (I can unlock it and change it if need be—this is just to let the whole drive team know that the auto is ready to go).</li>
<li>When the robot is positioned on the field before the match and it connects to our driver station, the robot <em>loads in</em> the auto that is saved on the computer.  We don’t need to redeploy, and we can edit our auto in queue, during robot placement, or even during team introductions.</li>
</ol>
<p>As someone who has only ever used Shuffleboard for auto config, I have no idea how to implement this system.  PathPlanner seems like the closest existing tool, but they specifically say not to use their hot reloading feature during competitions.  What do more advanced teams do?  Does anyone have recommendations of how to implement the system I described?<br>
Thanks for any thoughts you have.</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2024-09-20T20:55:04.127Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":28,"reads":635,"readers_count":634,"score":267.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":471543,"topic_slug":"flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it","display_username":"Sam","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":62962,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"FRC Team Software Lead"},"post_url":"/t/flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it/471543/1","custom_user_title":"FRC Team Software Lead","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3425609,"name":"","username":"Nimble","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/a5b964/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-09-20T21:01:36.251Z","cooked":"<p>What you could do is make a bunch of trajectories (not full paths, just segments) on pathplanner. You could then create a sort of draggable list where you can add, rearrange, or remove segments until you have comparable paths. You could add in commands wherever is appropriate.</p>
<p>However, there are many liabilities with this system. What if you mess up a path or forget to add segments? What if you run out of time? I’d say it’s best to create pre designed routines using pathplanner &amp; test them, rather than making responsive autos.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2024-09-20T21:01:52.277Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":576,"readers_count":575,"score":130.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":471543,"topic_slug":"flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":56803,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it/471543/2","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3425613,"name":"UnofficialForth","username":"UnofficialForth","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/unofficialforth/{size}/167902_2.png","created_at":"2024-09-20T21:14:21.861Z","cooked":"<p><a class="mention" href="/u/nimble">@Nimble</a> is correct in saying all this could be done with path-planner. Don’t try to reinvent the wheel, that’s literally the point of coding libraries and developed applications.</p>
<p>In order to be flexible, you have to know you can do flexible correctly every time no matter what. You will want to design a very robust auto system that you don’t ever have to test. This is a difficult problem to solve because it is often more advantageous to create 2-3 really quick autos that you spend lots of time tuning than an unlimited supply of slower ones.</p>
<p>We are starting to experiment with on-the-fly auto making, and it starts with creating a discipline approach that will guarantee that we can do something like that in the heat of the moment. It’s a lot of work, but can be done. It’s your job to prove to yourself that it can be done every single time no matter what.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2024-09-20T21:14:21.861Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":542,"readers_count":541,"score":123.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":471543,"topic_slug":"flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it","display_username":"UnofficialForth","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":29982,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"FRC Team 4272  Mentor | World's FLL Emcee"},"post_url":"/t/flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it/471543/3","custom_user_title":"FRC Team 4272  Mentor | World's FLL Emcee","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3425633,"name":"2582","username":"chadr03","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/chadr03/{size}/195529_2.png","created_at":"2024-09-20T22:35:49.725Z","cooked":"<p>I may be too conservative on my approach, but I really do not like to run autos in a match that we have not tested.  We may just slightly inch waypoints or adjust pauses, but still at least try to run those before we go live on the field even if it is just on blocks in our pit to make sure there are no surprises.</p>
<p>It is not always possible to test pre match and with the a-stop much less of a risk than it was in the past. But an auto that goes way wrong can wreck your entire march.</p>
<p>Pathplanner is an awesome tool and many times a new path/auto just works, but it seems the little things that your don’t think about until you actually see it run and go oh yeah we need to make those commands parallel and not series. Or that command never stops so our robot just sits there and does nothing often show up during testing.</p>
<p>I do however try to get my team to think about autos that other teams will do and make complementary autos that we have tested that can work with anyone without having to modify them pre match.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2024-09-20T22:35:49.725Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":457,"readers_count":456,"score":181.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":471543,"topic_slug":"flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it","display_username":"2582","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":6}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":13827,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it/471543/4","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":3},{"id":"point_up","type":"emoji","count":2},{"id":"+1","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":6,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3425641,"name":"Eli Barnett","username":"Oblarg","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/oblarg/{size}/161674_2.png","created_at":"2024-09-20T23:09:58.614Z","cooked":"<p>The key to making flexible software is modularity.  Don’t represent your auto routine with a monocommand; break it into parts.  You can use a tool like pathplanner to make those parts, but don’t rely on it to put them together.  It cannot really do that dynamically; you have to code that yourself.</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2024-09-20T23:15:21.394Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":388,"readers_count":387,"score":112.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":471543,"topic_slug":"flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it","display_username":"Eli Barnett","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":12381,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Robot apartments! invisible suburbs! skeleton treasuries!"},"post_url":"/t/flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it/471543/5","custom_user_title":"Robot apartments! invisible suburbs! skeleton treasuries!","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":2}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":2,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3425703,"name":"Sam Carlberg","username":"SamCarlberg","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/samcarlberg/{size}/207684_2.png","created_at":"2024-09-21T02:04:57.099Z","cooked":"<p>This is really the key. Instead of having a single path for a full autonomous, split the path into separate segments and tie them together at runtime based on the selections you make on your dashboard. Bonus points for using conditionals for picking a different segment after some decision point (such as using vision to check if your first choice game piece is available) instead of blindly following the path.</p>
<p>Something like this (hopefully the pseudocode gets the point across). Assumes all the trajectory segments are pregenerated and you’ve written some logic to determine which segment to follow based on known starting and target positions.</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">SendableChooser&lt;StartingPosition&gt; startingPositionChooser;
SendableChooser&lt;NoteLocation&gt; firstChoiceNoteChooser;
SendableChooser&lt;NoteLocation&gt; backupNoteChooser;

@Override
public void autonomousInit() {
  var startingPosition = startingPositionChooser.getSelected();
  var firstChoiceNote = firstChoiceNoteChooser.getSelected();
  var backupNote = backupNoteChooser.getSelected();

  var trajStart = getTrajectoryStart(startingPosition, firstChoiceNote);
  var preferredPickup = getTrajectoryEnd(startingPosition, firstChoiceNote);
  var backupPickup = getTrajectoryEnd(startingPosition, backupNote);

  Command conditionalPathingCommand =
    followTrajectory(trajStart)
      .andThen(
        Commands.either(
          followTrajectory(preferredPickup),
          followTrajectory(backupPickup),
          () -&gt; vision.seesNote(firstChoiceNote)));
}
</code></pre>
<p>The implementation will be a lot simpler in 2027 when we can use coroutines on the new MRC, but it’s still fundamentally about breaking up a large problem into many smaller parts that can be dynamically combined. When you think about it, that’s basically the essence of software engineering.</p>","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2024-09-21T02:04:57.099Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":4,"reads":355,"readers_count":354,"score":201.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":471543,"topic_slug":"flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it","display_username":"Sam Carlberg","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":12381,"username":"Oblarg","name":"Eli Barnett","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/oblarg/{size}/161674_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":7}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":25916,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"2084 Lead Mentor | WPILib Developer"},"post_url":"/t/flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it/471543/6","custom_user_title":"2084 Lead Mentor | WPILib Developer","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":7}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":7,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3425726,"name":"Sam","username":"Paraduks","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/ea5d25/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-09-21T04:06:39.904Z","cooked":"<p>Thanks everyone!  This perspective is helpful.  One thing I am wondering is how people set up the interface for configuring the auto.  I could make many different paths and sequences in PathPlanner, but from what you are suggesting it seems like the actual building of your auto would be done through dropdowns in Shuffleboard.  Is there a more visual way to do it?  Ideally, I would like to be able to play through the combined sequence of autos, and see them laid out on a field map.</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2024-09-21T04:06:39.904Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":6,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":272,"readers_count":271,"score":59.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":471543,"topic_slug":"flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it","display_username":"Sam","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":25916,"username":"SamCarlberg","name":"Sam Carlberg","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/samcarlberg/{size}/207684_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":62962,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"FRC Team Software Lead"},"post_url":"/t/flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it/471543/7","custom_user_title":"FRC Team Software Lead","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3425735,"name":"Avi","username":"Avi","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/avi/{size}/214903_2.png","created_at":"2024-09-21T04:45:19.937Z","cooked":"<p>You could make an app that lets you drag premade auto trajectories together. Then it would list the correct drop down menu settings to apply to get those trajectories.</p>","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2024-09-21T04:45:19.937Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":7,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":250,"readers_count":249,"score":55.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":471543,"topic_slug":"flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it","display_username":"Avi","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":62962,"username":"Paraduks","name":"Sam","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/ea5d25/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":55766,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it/471543/8","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3426090,"name":"Sam","username":"Paraduks","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/ea5d25/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-09-22T16:54:24.272Z","cooked":"<p>How would you recommend doing this?  It’s a similar project as PathPlanner, but it would be made for quick prematch configuration, and built to supply the robot with a config when it turns on  Could a part of PathPlanner be used?  Or should I build my own gui?  If I did build my own app, I would probably use Unity, as that’s what me and my coders are familiar with.  How would I handle the network tables interaction if I were to build my own app?  Thanks for your recommendation</p>","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2024-09-22T16:54:24.272Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":8,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":193,"readers_count":192,"score":43.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":471543,"topic_slug":"flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it","display_username":"Sam","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":55766,"username":"Avi","name":"Avi","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/avi/{size}/214903_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":62962,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"FRC Team Software Lead"},"post_url":"/t/flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it/471543/9","custom_user_title":"FRC Team Software Lead","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3426097,"name":"Avi","username":"Avi","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/avi/{size}/214903_2.png","created_at":"2024-09-22T17:13:47.319Z","cooked":"<p>what I’m suggesting is you make an app that doesn’t communicate with the robot. Instead it can translate a visual into a list of settings that you can enter into Shuffleboard. The goal here being to find a compromise between having a visual and using shuffleboard choosers to communicate to the robot.</p>
<p>My first thought of how to do this would be to just have a picture of the field which you can overlay various trajectories. Then write a script that corresponds the trajectories and their order into a list of selections for drop downs in Shuffleboard.</p>","post_number":10,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2024-09-22T17:13:47.319Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":9,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":181,"readers_count":180,"score":46.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":471543,"topic_slug":"flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it","display_username":"Avi","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":62962,"username":"Paraduks","name":"Sam","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/ea5d25/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":55766,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/flexible-autos-how-do-teams-do-it/471543/10","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3426106,"name":"Sam","username":"Paraduks","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/ea5d25/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-09-22T17:36:56.449Z","cooked":"<p>Thanks, that makes sense.  In terms of functionality though, could this be done simply by making the auto in PathPlanner and then pasting the “.auto” json into a text input in Shuffleboard?  That would be a janky way to do it, but it would accomplish